Actually, digging a bit deeper into it, I think the problem is different.

Werkzeug's form data parser [kicks-in](https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/blob/master/werkzeug/wrappers.py#L355) if the Content-Type header is set. The form parser [first checks](https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/blob/master/werkzeug/formparser.py#L184-L187) if Content-Length exceeds maximum allowed length, then try to [find a suitable parser function](https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/blob/master/werkzeug/formparser.py#L191) for a given MIME type. All this is executed when Flask-OAuthlib calls ``request.form.to_dict()``.

We have set ``MAX_CONTENT_LENGTH`` in Files-REST to ~15mb, since anything above 500kb will be written to a temporary file, this possible exhausting the local disk (i.e. it makes sense to put a limit). However, in Files-REST we also want to allow very large file uploads in a single request via streaming the file in the body (and reading it from ``request.stream`` without writing it to temporary file on disk). 

If Werkzeug's form parser reversed the order to 1) find suitable parser for MIME type, then 2) check content length, then calls to ``request.form`` (like the one from Flask-OAuthlib) wouldn't be an issue, because Werkzeug wouldn't even try to read the data. I.e. change [this](https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/blob/master/werkzeug/formparser.py#L173-L200), into something like this:

```python
def parse(self, stream, mimetype, content_length, options=None):
    if options is None:
        options = {}

    parse_func = self.get_parse_func(mimetype, options)
    if parse_func is not None:
        if self.max_content_length is not None and \
           content_length is not None and \
           content_length > self.max_content_length:
            raise exceptions.RequestEntityTooLarge()
        
        try:
            return parse_func(self, stream, mimetype,
                              content_length, options)
        except ValueError:
            if not self.silent:
                raise

    return stream, self.cls(), self.cls()
```

